LONG_CONTEXT = [
    {"id": "long_001", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I'm working on a research project about renewable energy sources. We've been studying solar panels, wind turbines, and hydroelectric dams for the past six months. Our team consists of twelve researchers from various universities across Europe. The project is funded by a European Union grant that covers our expenses through 2027. Last week we visited a solar farm in southern Spain that generates over 500 megawatts of power. The facility covers an area of approximately 2,000 acres and uses over a million individual solar panels. During our visit, we learned that the farm was built in 2019 and cost approximately 600 million euros to construct. The farm employs about 300 workers for maintenance and operations. According to the facility manager, the farm produces enough electricity to power 250,000 homes. My question is: how many homes does the solar farm power?"}],
     "reference_answer": "250,000 homes"},
    {"id": "long_002", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The history of computing is a fascinating journey through human ingenuity and technological progress. In the early 1800s, Charles Babbage designed the Analytical Engine, which is often considered the first general-purpose computer concept. Ada Lovelace wrote what is considered the first computer program for this machine. Moving forward to the 1930s, Alan Turing developed the concept of the Turing machine, which formalized the concept of computation. During World War II, the Colossus computer was built to break German codes, and ENIAC was developed in the United States for ballistic calculations. The transistor was invented in 1947 at Bell Labs, which eventually led to the development of integrated circuits. The first microprocessor, the Intel 4004, was released in 1971. Personal computers became widespread in the 1980s, and the World Wide Web was invented by Tim Berners-Lee in 1989. The question I want to ask is: in what year was the first microprocessor released?"}],
     "reference_answer": "1971"},
    {"id": "long_003", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "What is the name of the restaurant that Maria recommended? Here is the context: I was talking to my friend Maria last weekend about places to eat in the city. She mentioned several options including a Thai restaurant on Oak Street, an Italian place near the park, and a Mexican restaurant downtown. She said the Italian place, called Bella Notte, had the best pasta she'd ever tasted. The Thai restaurant was good but expensive, and the Mexican place was cheap but crowded. She also mentioned a new French bistro that just opened but hadn't tried it yet. Maria has been living in the city for over ten years and knows all the best spots. She works as a food critic for the local newspaper, so I trust her opinion on restaurants more than most people. She told me she visits at least three new restaurants every week as part of her job. The restaurant she recommended most highly was Bella Notte."}],
     "reference_answer": "Bella Notte"},
    {"id": "long_004", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Let me describe a complex scenario involving several characters and their relationships. David is a software engineer who works at TechCorp in Seattle. His colleague, Priya, manages the data science team. Together, they are working on a machine learning project to predict customer churn. The project was initiated by the VP of Engineering, Marcus Chen, who believes the company is losing too many customers to competitors. The project budget is $2.5 million, and it needs to be completed by December. David's team has 8 engineers, and Priya's team has 5 data scientists. They also hired an external consultant named Yuki who specializes in deep learning architectures. Yuki previously worked at a major AI research lab and has published over 30 papers. The project's code name is Project Phoenix. What is the budget of Project Phoenix?"}],
     "reference_answer": "$2.5 million"},
    {"id": "long_005", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The Amazon rainforest is the world's largest tropical rainforest, covering approximately 5.5 million square kilometers across nine countries in South America. It is home to an estimated 10% of all species on Earth, including over 40,000 plant species, 1,300 bird species, and 3,000 types of fish. The forest plays a crucial role in regulating the global climate by absorbing massive amounts of carbon dioxide and producing oxygen. Scientists often refer to it as the lungs of the Earth, though this is somewhat misleading as the forest consumes nearly as much oxygen as it produces. Deforestation has been a major concern, with an estimated 17% of the forest lost in the last 50 years. The main drivers of deforestation are cattle ranching, soybean farming, and illegal logging. Indigenous communities have lived in the Amazon for thousands of years, and there are still approximately 400 indigenous tribes, some of which have had no contact with the outside world. The Brazilian government has established various protected areas, but enforcement remains challenging. According to recent satellite data, the rate of deforestation increased by 22% in the past year. What percentage of the Amazon rainforest has been lost in the last 50 years?"}],
     "reference_answer": "17%"},
    {"id": "long_006", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "My grandmother used to tell me stories about her childhood in a small village in southern Italy. She was born in 1935 in a village called Montepulciano, which sits on a hilltop in Tuscany. Her family owned a small olive grove that had been in the family for generations. She was the youngest of seven children, and her father was a local schoolteacher. During World War II, the village was briefly occupied by German soldiers, and her family hid two British soldiers in their barn for three weeks. After the war, her oldest brother emigrated to Argentina, and another sister moved to Australia. My grandmother herself moved to the United States in 1958, settling in Brooklyn, New York. She met my grandfather, Antonio, at a church social in 1960, and they married the following year. They opened a bakery on Atlantic Avenue that became famous in the neighborhood for its cannoli. The bakery operated for 35 years before they retired. How many children were in my grandmother's family?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Seven children"},
    {"id": "long_007", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The theory of plate tectonics revolutionized our understanding of Earth's geology. The theory proposes that Earth's outer shell, the lithosphere, is divided into several large plates that float on the semi-fluid asthenosphere below. These plates move relative to one another at speeds ranging from 1 to 10 centimeters per year. Where plates converge, one plate may be forced beneath another in a process called subduction, which creates deep ocean trenches and volcanic arcs. Where plates diverge, new crust is formed as magma rises from the mantle, creating mid-ocean ridges. The theory was primarily developed by Alfred Wegener, who proposed continental drift in 1912, though it was not widely accepted until the 1960s when evidence from seafloor spreading confirmed the mechanism. The San Andreas Fault in California is an example of a transform boundary where two plates slide past each other. The Pacific Ring of Fire, which encircles the Pacific Ocean, is the most geologically active zone on Earth, with approximately 75% of the world's active volcanoes located along it. What percentage of the world's active volcanoes are in the Ring of Fire?"}],
     "reference_answer": "75%"},
    {"id": "long_008", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I recently attended a conference on artificial intelligence in healthcare. The keynote speaker was Dr. Sarah Kim from Stanford University. She presented findings from a study that used deep learning to detect early-stage lung cancer from CT scans. The study involved 42,000 patients across 15 hospitals in the United States and Europe. The AI system achieved a sensitivity of 94.4% and specificity of 96.1%, outperforming a panel of six experienced radiologists. The study was published in Nature Medicine and took three years to complete. Dr. Kim mentioned that the system was trained on over 2 million CT scan images using a modified ResNet architecture with attention mechanisms. The most interesting part was that the AI could detect cancers an average of 1.2 years earlier than human radiologists. The FDA has approved the system for clinical use as a screening tool, though it is not yet approved for diagnosis. Several other talks covered topics like drug discovery, protein folding, and mental health monitoring using smartphone data. What was the sensitivity of the AI lung cancer detection system?"}],
     "reference_answer": "94.4%"},
    {"id": "long_009", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Let me tell you about the architecture of our new building. The structure is a 45-story mixed-use tower designed by renowned architect Zaha Hadid Architects. The building features a distinctive curved facade made of double-paned glass panels that reduce energy consumption by 30%. The first 10 floors house commercial office space, floors 11 through 30 contain residential apartments ranging from studios to three-bedroom units, and floors 31 through 45 are luxury penthouses. The building has three underground parking levels with space for 500 vehicles. A rooftop garden on the 45th floor includes a swimming pool, a running track, and a small urban farm. The building's total construction cost was $890 million, and it was completed in 18 months using modular construction techniques. The lobby features a 40-foot atrium with a water feature designed by artist James Turrell. The building achieved LEED Platinum certification for its sustainable design features, including solar panels that generate 15% of the building's electricity needs. How many stories does the building have?"}],
     "reference_answer": "45 stories"},
    {"id": "long_010", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The human immune system is a remarkably complex network of cells, tissues, and organs that work together to defend the body against pathogens. The system can be broadly divided into two categories: innate immunity, which provides immediate but non-specific defense, and adaptive immunity, which develops over time and provides specific, targeted responses. White blood cells, or leukocytes, are the primary soldiers of the immune system. Among these, T cells and B cells play crucial roles in adaptive immunity. T cells are produced in the bone marrow but mature in the thymus, while B cells mature in the bone marrow. When a pathogen enters the body, antigen-presenting cells capture and display fragments of the pathogen to T cells. Helper T cells then activate B cells, which produce antibodies specific to the pathogen. Memory cells are also created, which allow for a faster response if the same pathogen is encountered again. This is the principle behind vaccination. Interestingly, the human gut contains approximately 70% of the body's immune cells, highlighting the importance of gut health for overall immunity. What percentage of the body's immune cells are in the gut?"}],
     "reference_answer": "70%"},
    {"id": "long_011", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I want to tell you about my recent hiking trip to Patagonia. We started from El Calafate in Argentina and spent 12 days trekking through Torres del Paine National Park in Chile. Our group consisted of 8 hikers and 2 professional guides. The weather was unpredictable, with temperatures ranging from -5 to 15 degrees Celsius. On day three, we reached the base of the famous Torres, three granite towers that rise to approximately 2,500 meters. The hike to the base took 9 hours round trip and was the most physically demanding day. On day five, we crossed the French Valley, which offered stunning views of hanging glaciers. The highlight for me was day seven when we reached the Grey Glacier viewpoint. The glacier is approximately 6 km wide and 30 meters tall at its face. We could hear the ice cracking and saw several icebergs calving into the lake. Our longest day was day eight, when we covered 28 kilometers. By the end of the trip, we had covered a total of 130 kilometers. How many total kilometers did the group cover on the trip?"}],
     "reference_answer": "130 kilometers"},
    {"id": "long_012", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The development of quantum computing represents one of the most exciting frontiers in technology. Unlike classical computers that use bits representing 0 or 1, quantum computers use qubits that can exist in superposition, representing both 0 and 1 simultaneously. This property, along with entanglement, allows quantum computers to perform certain calculations exponentially faster than classical computers. IBM currently leads in terms of quantum processor size, with their latest chip containing 1,121 qubits, though most of these are not yet error-corrected. Google achieved what they called quantum supremacy in 2019 when their Sycamore processor performed a specific calculation in 200 seconds that would take the world's fastest supercomputer approximately 10,000 years. However, the practical applications of quantum computing are still limited. The most promising near-term applications include drug discovery, materials science, cryptography, and optimization problems. A major challenge remains quantum decoherence, where qubits lose their quantum state due to environmental interference. Companies are exploring various approaches to build more stable qubits, including superconducting circuits, trapped ions, and topological qubits. How many qubits does IBM's latest chip contain?"}],
     "reference_answer": "1,121 qubits"},
    {"id": "long_013", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Our company just completed its annual financial review. Total revenue for the fiscal year was $45.3 million, up 12% from the previous year. Operating expenses were $38.7 million, resulting in an operating profit of $6.6 million. The largest expense category was personnel costs at $22.1 million, followed by technology infrastructure at $8.4 million, and marketing at $5.2 million. We opened three new offices in Austin, Portland, and Miami, bringing our total office count to 11. Headcount grew from 380 to 425 employees, a 12% increase. Customer retention rate improved from 87% to 91%, which the board was particularly pleased about. Our biggest product launch was the Enterprise Analytics Suite, which generated $8.2 million in its first year. The board approved a capital expenditure budget of $5 million for next year, primarily for upgrading our cloud infrastructure. What was the company's total revenue?"}],
     "reference_answer": "$45.3 million"},
    {"id": "long_014", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The history of coffee is rich and spans several centuries. Legend has it that coffee was first discovered by an Ethiopian goat herder named Kaldi around the 9th century, who noticed his goats became energetic after eating certain berries. The beans were first cultivated in Yemen in the 15th century, where Sufi monks used the drink to stay awake during nighttime prayers. Coffee houses, known as qahveh khaneh, spread rapidly across the Middle East and became important social gathering places. Coffee reached Europe in the 17th century and was initially met with suspicion, with some calling it the bitter invention of Satan. Pope Clement VIII reportedly blessed coffee after tasting it, declaring it a Christian beverage. The first European coffee house opened in Venice in 1645. In 1773, the Boston Tea Party made coffee the preferred patriotic drink in America. Today, coffee is the second most traded commodity in the world after crude oil. Brazil is the world's largest coffee producer, generating approximately 37% of the world's supply. An estimated 2.25 billion cups of coffee are consumed worldwide every day. What percentage of the world's coffee does Brazil produce?"}],
     "reference_answer": "37%"},
    {"id": "long_015", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I need help understanding a complex scenario in my chess game. I'm playing white and it's move 23. My king is on g1, my queen is on d3, I have rooks on a1 and f1, bishops on c1 and e2, knights on f3 and d2, and pawns on a2, b2, c3, e4, f2, g2, h3. My opponent has their king on g8, queen on d7, rooks on a8 and e8, bishops on c8 and f6, a knight on c6, and pawns on a7, b7, c4, d6, f7, g7, h7. The position is tense with both sides having chances. I've been considering the move Nd2-b3 to attack the c4 pawn and potentially reroute the knight to a5 or d4. Another option is to play a4 to restrict the queenside. The computer evaluation shows the position at approximately +0.8 in my favor. Given all this, what square is my queen currently on?"}],
     "reference_answer": "d3"},
    {"id": "long_016", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The process of photosynthesis is fundamental to life on Earth. It occurs primarily in the chloroplasts of plant cells, specifically in structures called thylakoids. The process can be divided into two main stages: the light-dependent reactions and the Calvin cycle. In the light-dependent reactions, chlorophyll absorbs light energy, primarily in the blue and red wavelengths, and uses it to split water molecules into hydrogen ions, electrons, and oxygen. The oxygen is released as a byproduct, which is what we breathe. The electrons pass through an electron transport chain, generating ATP and NADPH. In the Calvin cycle, which takes place in the stroma of the chloroplast, carbon dioxide from the atmosphere is fixed into organic molecules using the ATP and NADPH produced in the light reactions. The enzyme RuBisCO catalyzes the first step of carbon fixation and is the most abundant protein on Earth. A single leaf can contain millions of chloroplasts, each performing photosynthesis simultaneously. On average, a mature tree can absorb about 22 kilograms of carbon dioxide per year and release enough oxygen for two people to breathe. How many kilograms of CO2 does a mature tree absorb per year?"}],
     "reference_answer": "22 kilograms"},
    {"id": "long_017", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I've been researching the Mars exploration program extensively. The first successful Mars flyby was Mariner 4 in 1965, which sent back 22 photographs. The first successful landing was Viking 1 in 1976, which searched for signs of life in the Martian soil. Since then, numerous missions have been sent, including Pathfinder with its Sojourner rover in 1997, the twin rovers Spirit and Opportunity in 2004, Curiosity in 2012, and most recently Perseverance in 2021. Perseverance landed in Jezero Crater, which scientists believe was once an ancient lake bed. The rover carries instruments for astrobiology research, including SHERLOC and PIXL for analyzing rock composition. It also carried Ingenuity, a small helicopter that became the first aircraft to achieve powered flight on another planet. China's Zhurong rover also landed on Mars in 2021, making China the second country to successfully operate a rover on Mars. SpaceX has announced plans for crewed Mars missions, with an optimistic timeline of the late 2020s. The one-way travel time to Mars is approximately 7 months with current propulsion technology. In what year did Viking 1 land on Mars?"}],
     "reference_answer": "1976"},
    {"id": "long_018", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Let me describe the recipe I followed for the dinner party last night. I made a classic Beef Bourguignon, which is a French stew from the Burgundy region. The recipe called for 2 pounds of beef chuck cut into 2-inch cubes, 6 strips of bacon, 1 bottle of red Burgundy wine, 2 cups of beef stock, 1 tablespoon of tomato paste, 4 cloves of garlic, 20 pearl onions, 1 pound of mushrooms, 3 carrots cut into chunks, and a bouquet garni of thyme, bay leaf, and parsley. First, I browned the bacon in a large Dutch oven, then removed it and browned the beef cubes in the bacon fat. I added the vegetables, then deglazed with the wine, added the stock and tomato paste, and brought it to a simmer. The dish cooked in the oven at 325 degrees Fahrenheit for 3 hours. While it was cooking, I sauteed the pearl onions and mushrooms separately in butter. These were added to the stew during the last 30 minutes. I served it with buttered egg noodles and a green salad. It served 8 people comfortably. The total preparation and cooking time was about 4.5 hours. At what temperature did the stew cook in the oven?"}],
     "reference_answer": "325 degrees Fahrenheit"},
    {"id": "long_019", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The ancient Egyptian civilization lasted for over three thousand years, from approximately 3100 BCE to 30 BCE. During this time, the Egyptians built the Great Pyramids of Giza, developed hieroglyphic writing, made advances in medicine, astronomy, and mathematics, and created one of the most sophisticated cultures in the ancient world. The Great Pyramid of Khufu, the largest of the three pyramids at Giza, was built around 2560 BCE and stood 146.6 meters tall, making it the tallest man-made structure in the world for over 3,800 years. The ancient Egyptians believed in an afterlife and developed elaborate mummification practices to preserve the body. The Rosetta Stone, discovered in 1799, was key to deciphering hieroglyphics, as it contained the same text in three scripts: hieroglyphic, demotic, and ancient Greek. The Egyptian civilization ended when Cleopatra VII, the last pharaoh, died in 30 BCE and Egypt became a Roman province. The Nile River was central to Egyptian civilization, providing water for irrigation, transportation, and fertile soil through annual flooding. How tall was the Great Pyramid of Khufu originally?"}],
     "reference_answer": "146.6 meters"},
    {"id": "long_020", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The global supply chain disruptions of recent years have highlighted the fragility of just-in-time manufacturing systems. When the Ever Given container ship blocked the Suez Canal in March 2021 for six days, it held up an estimated $9.6 billion worth of goods per day. The semiconductor shortage that began in 2020 affected industries from automotive to consumer electronics, with car manufacturers losing an estimated $210 billion in revenue in 2021 alone. Companies have since been reevaluating their supply chain strategies, with many adopting a just-in-case approach that involves holding larger inventories and diversifying suppliers across multiple regions. The concept of nearshoring has gained traction, with companies moving manufacturing closer to their primary markets. For example, Mexico has seen a significant increase in foreign direct investment as US companies seek alternatives to distant Asian manufacturing. The pandemic also accelerated the adoption of supply chain visibility tools, with companies investing in real-time tracking technologies, AI-powered demand forecasting, and blockchain-based provenance verification. How much revenue did car manufacturers lose due to the semiconductor shortage in 2021?"}],
     "reference_answer": "$210 billion"},
    {"id": "long_021", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The history of the Olympic Games stretches back to ancient Greece, where the first recorded games took place in 776 BCE in Olympia. The ancient games featured events like foot races, wrestling, boxing, and chariot racing, and continued for nearly 12 centuries until 393 CE when they were banned by Roman Emperor Theodosius I. The modern Olympic Games were revived by Pierre de Coubertin in 1896 in Athens, Greece, with 14 nations and 241 athletes competing. The games have grown enormously since then. The 2020 Tokyo Olympics, held in 2021 due to the pandemic, featured over 11,000 athletes from 206 countries competing in 339 events across 33 sports. The most decorated Olympian of all time is Michael Phelps, who won 28 medals including 23 gold medals in swimming. The Winter Olympics were first held separately in 1924 in Chamonix, France. The International Olympic Committee, headquartered in Lausanne, Switzerland, oversees both the Summer and Winter Games. How many gold medals did Michael Phelps win?"}],
     "reference_answer": "23 gold medals"},
    {"id": "long_022", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I'm preparing a detailed travel itinerary for a trip to Japan. Day 1-3: Tokyo. We'll visit Sensoji Temple, Akihabara, Shibuya Crossing, and the Meiji Shrine. Our hotel is the Park Hyatt in Shinjuku, which is where the movie Lost in Translation was filmed. Day 4: Take the bullet train to Hakone, enjoy the hot springs, and see Mount Fuji if weather permits. Day 5-6: Kyoto. Visit Fushimi Inari with its thousands of torii gates, Kinkaku-ji (the Golden Pavilion), and Arashiyama Bamboo Grove. Stay at a traditional ryokan. Day 7: Day trip to Nara to see the friendly deer and Todai-ji Temple, which houses a giant bronze Buddha that is 15 meters tall. Day 8-9: Osaka. Focus on food, particularly the Dotonbori district. Try takoyaki, okonomiyaki, and visit Osaka Castle. Day 10: Travel to Hiroshima and visit the Peace Memorial Park. Day 11: Visit Miyajima Island to see the floating torii gate. Day 12: Return to Tokyo for departure. Total budget for the trip is approximately $8,000 per person. How tall is the bronze Buddha at Todai-ji Temple?"}],
     "reference_answer": "15 meters"},
    {"id": "long_023", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Understanding neural networks requires grasping several key concepts. At the most basic level, a neural network consists of layers of interconnected nodes, or neurons, inspired by biological neural networks. Each connection has a weight that is adjusted during training. The input layer receives data, hidden layers process it through weighted sums and activation functions, and the output layer produces the result. The most common activation functions are ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit), sigmoid, and tanh. Training involves forward propagation, where input data flows through the network to produce an output, and backpropagation, where the error between the predicted and actual output is propagated backward through the network to adjust the weights. The learning rate controls how much the weights are adjusted in each step. Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) are specialized for image processing, using convolutional layers that apply filters to detect features like edges and textures. Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) are designed for sequential data like text and time series. Transformers, introduced in the 2017 paper 'Attention Is All You Need', have largely replaced RNNs for natural language processing. The original transformer model had 65 million parameters. How many parameters did the original transformer model have?"}],
     "reference_answer": "65 million parameters"},
    {"id": "long_024", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The city planning committee held its quarterly meeting last Tuesday to discuss several major infrastructure projects. The first item on the agenda was the new light rail extension, which will add 14 kilometers of track connecting the downtown core to the northern suburbs. The project is budgeted at $3.2 billion and is expected to be completed by 2029. Next, they discussed the renovation of Central Park, including new playground equipment, a splash pad, an outdoor amphitheater, and improved lighting throughout. This project has a budget of $45 million. The committee also reviewed the status of the water treatment plant upgrade, which is currently 67% complete and on schedule. The fourth topic was the controversial proposal to build a new sports stadium near the waterfront. The stadium would seat 60,000 spectators and cost an estimated $1.8 billion, with the city contributing 40% and private developers covering the rest. Community input sessions revealed that 58% of residents surveyed opposed public funding for the stadium. The meeting concluded with a discussion about pothole repairs and street resurfacing priorities for the coming quarter. How many kilometers will the light rail extension add?"}],
     "reference_answer": "14 kilometers"},
    {"id": "long_025", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I want to share details about the wildlife sanctuary I visited in Costa Rica. The sanctuary covers 1,200 hectares of tropical rainforest and cloud forest. It was established in 1992 by a German biologist named Dr. Klaus Weber, who purchased the land to protect it from logging companies. The sanctuary is home to 347 species of birds, including the resplendent quetzal, 89 species of mammals, 56 species of reptiles, and over 6,000 species of insects. The centerpiece of the sanctuary is a 2-kilometer canopy walkway suspended 45 meters above the forest floor, which offers visitors an unparalleled view of the forest canopy ecosystem. During my visit, I saw three different species of monkeys: howler monkeys, spider monkeys, and capuchins. The guide told us that the sanctuary receives about 50,000 visitors per year and all entrance fees go directly toward conservation efforts. They also run a breeding program for endangered scarlet macaws, having successfully released 150 birds back into the wild over the past decade. How many hectares does the sanctuary cover?"}],
     "reference_answer": "1,200 hectares"},
    {"id": "long_026", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "My grandfather was a submarine captain in the Royal Navy during the Cold War. He commanded HMS Sceptre, a Swiftsure-class nuclear submarine, from 1978 to 1983. The submarine was 82.9 meters long and could dive to a depth of 400 meters. It had a crew of 116 men and could stay submerged for months at a time, limited only by food supplies. He told me stories about patrolling the North Atlantic, tracking Soviet submarines during the tensest years of the Cold War. The most dangerous mission he described was in 1981, when they were tasked with following a Soviet Typhoon-class ballistic missile submarine through the Norwegian Sea. The Typhoon was the largest submarine ever built, at 175 meters long. My grandfather said the tensest moment was when they lost track of the Soviet sub in a thermal layer and had to go silent for 72 hours. After retiring from the Navy, he became a maritime consultant and helped design navigation systems for civilian vessels. He passed away in 2015 at the age of 82. How long was HMS Sceptre?"}],
     "reference_answer": "82.9 meters"},
    {"id": "long_027", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The development of vaccines has been one of the greatest achievements in public health history. Edward Jenner developed the first vaccine in 1796 using cowpox material to provide immunity against smallpox. Louis Pasteur later developed vaccines for rabies and anthrax in the 1880s. The 20th century saw rapid vaccine development, with vaccines for polio (both Salk's inactivated vaccine in 1955 and Sabin's oral vaccine in 1961), measles (1963), and many others. The WHO declared smallpox eradicated in 1980, the only human disease to have been completely eliminated through vaccination. The development of mRNA vaccine technology, pioneered by Katalin Kariko and Drew Weissman, enabled the rapid creation of COVID-19 vaccines in 2020. Moderna and Pfizer-BioNTech both produced mRNA vaccines that showed approximately 95% efficacy in clinical trials. As of 2023, over 13 billion COVID-19 vaccine doses have been administered worldwide. Current research focuses on developing universal influenza vaccines, malaria vaccines, and cancer vaccines using mRNA technology. In what year was smallpox declared eradicated by the WHO?"}],
     "reference_answer": "1980"},
    {"id": "long_028", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I need to explain our software architecture for the code review. Our application uses a microservices architecture deployed on Kubernetes. The main services include: the API Gateway (written in Go, handles 10,000 requests per second), the User Service (Python/FastAPI, manages authentication and user profiles), the Payment Service (Java/Spring Boot, processes transactions via Stripe), the Notification Service (Node.js, handles email, SMS, and push notifications), and the Analytics Service (Python, processes event streams using Apache Kafka). Data is stored across PostgreSQL for relational data, Redis for caching and session management, and Elasticsearch for full-text search. Each service has its own database following the database-per-service pattern. We use gRPC for inter-service communication and REST for external APIs. The CI/CD pipeline uses GitHub Actions with automated testing, security scanning, and deployment to AWS EKS. Our current infrastructure costs are approximately $47,000 per month. The team consists of 15 backend engineers, 8 frontend engineers, 3 DevOps engineers, and 4 QA engineers. What is the monthly infrastructure cost?"}],
     "reference_answer": "$47,000"},
    {"id": "long_029", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The Voyager space missions represent humanity's farthest reach into space. Voyager 1 was launched on September 5, 1977, and Voyager 2 was launched 16 days earlier on August 20, 1977. Despite being launched second, Voyager 1 reached Jupiter and Saturn first due to its faster trajectory. Voyager 1 flew past Jupiter in March 1979 and Saturn in November 1980. Voyager 2 visited all four outer planets: Jupiter (1979), Saturn (1981), Uranus (1986), and Neptune (1989), making it the only spacecraft to have visited all four. In 2012, Voyager 1 became the first human-made object to enter interstellar space, crossing the heliopause at a distance of about 121 astronomical units from the Sun. Voyager 2 followed into interstellar space in 2018. Both spacecraft carry a Golden Record containing sounds and images selected to portray the diversity of life on Earth, in case the spacecraft are ever found by extraterrestrial life. As of 2024, Voyager 1 is approximately 24.3 billion kilometers from Earth and still transmitting data, though several instruments have been shut down to conserve power. How far from Earth is Voyager 1 as of 2024?"}],
     "reference_answer": "24.3 billion kilometers"},
    {"id": "long_030", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I've been studying the wine regions of France for my sommelier certification. Bordeaux is the largest fine wine region, producing approximately 700 million bottles per year. It is divided into Left Bank (dominated by Cabernet Sauvignon) and Right Bank (dominated by Merlot). Burgundy is known for single-varietal wines: Pinot Noir for reds and Chardonnay for whites. The classification system there is based on terroir, with Grand Cru at the top. Champagne, of course, produces the famous sparkling wine using the methode champenoise. The region produces about 300 million bottles annually. The Rhone Valley is divided into Northern Rhone (known for Syrah) and Southern Rhone (known for Grenache-based blends like Chateauneuf-du-Pape). The Loire Valley produces diverse wines including Sancerre (Sauvignon Blanc), Vouvray (Chenin Blanc), and Chinon (Cabernet Franc). Alsace, near the German border, specializes in aromatic whites like Riesling and Gewurztraminer. In total, France has over 300 distinct appellations and produces approximately 7-8 billion bottles of wine per year, making it the world's second-largest producer after Italy. How many bottles does Bordeaux produce per year?"}],
     "reference_answer": "700 million bottles"},
    {"id": "long_031", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Let me describe the scientific expedition to the Mariana Trench that I read about. The expedition took place in 2022 using a deep-sea submersible called the DSV Limiting Factor, piloted by explorer Victor Vescovo. The team made a total of 7 dives over three weeks, reaching a maximum depth of 10,928 meters at the Challenger Deep, the deepest known point in the ocean. The pressure at that depth is approximately 1,086 bars, or about 1,000 times the atmospheric pressure at sea level. Despite the extreme conditions, the team discovered over 40 previously unknown species, including several types of amphipods, sea cucumbers, and translucent fish. They also found microplastic particles at the deepest point, a sobering reminder of human pollution. The submersible was equipped with high-definition cameras, mechanical arms for sample collection, and a suite of sensors measuring temperature, salinity, and chemical composition of the water. The water temperature at the bottom was a constant 1 to 4 degrees Celsius. Each dive lasted approximately 12 hours, with about 4 hours spent at the bottom. How many previously unknown species were discovered?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Over 40 species"},
    {"id": "long_032", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The debate over artificial general intelligence continues to divide the AI research community. Some researchers, like Ray Kurzweil, predict AGI will be achieved by 2029, while others like Yann LeCun argue we are still missing fundamental breakthroughs needed for true general intelligence. Current large language models, despite their impressive capabilities, are considered narrow AI because they operate within specific domains and lack genuine understanding. The concept of the technological singularity, first popularized by Vernor Vinge in 1993 and later by Kurzweil, suggests that once AGI is achieved, it could rapidly improve itself, leading to an intelligence explosion. Critics argue this is speculative and ignores fundamental physical limitations on computation. The AI safety community, led by organizations like MIRI, the Center for AI Safety, and Anthropic, focuses on ensuring that advanced AI systems are aligned with human values. OpenAI, founded in 2015 with $1 billion in initial funding, has the stated mission of ensuring artificial general intelligence benefits all of humanity. DeepMind, acquired by Google for $500 million in 2014, has made significant advances including AlphaGo, AlphaFold, and Gemini. How much initial funding did OpenAI have?"}],
     "reference_answer": "$1 billion"},
    {"id": "long_033", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The Great Barrier Reef is the world's largest coral reef system, stretching over 2,300 kilometers along the northeast coast of Australia. It comprises approximately 2,900 individual reefs and 900 islands. The reef is visible from space and is the largest structure made by living organisms. It supports an incredible biodiversity, including over 1,500 species of fish, 411 types of hard coral, 134 species of sharks and rays, and 6 species of sea turtles. The reef was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1981. However, it faces significant threats from climate change, with rising ocean temperatures causing mass coral bleaching events. Major bleaching events occurred in 1998, 2002, 2016, 2017, 2020, and 2022. In the 2016 event alone, approximately 29% of shallow-water corals died. Ocean acidification, caused by increased CO2 absorption, also threatens coral growth by making it harder for corals to build their calcium carbonate skeletons. The Australian government has committed $4.4 billion to reef protection over the next decade. How many species of fish live in the Great Barrier Reef?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Over 1,500 species"},
    {"id": "long_034", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The Renaissance was a cultural movement that began in Florence, Italy, in the 14th century and spread across Europe over the next three centuries. It marked a transition from the medieval period to the early modern age, characterized by a renewed interest in classical Greek and Roman culture, humanism, and scientific inquiry. Key figures include Leonardo da Vinci, who painted the Mona Lisa and The Last Supper and made groundbreaking studies in anatomy, engineering, and optics. Michelangelo sculpted the David and painted the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel, which took him approximately 4 years to complete (1508-1512) and covers over 500 square meters. Raphael painted The School of Athens, and Botticelli created The Birth of Venus. In literature, Dante wrote the Divine Comedy, Petrarch is often called the father of humanism, and Machiavelli wrote The Prince. The invention of the printing press by Johannes Gutenberg around 1440 dramatically accelerated the spread of Renaissance ideas across Europe. The Renaissance also saw major advances in science, with Copernicus proposing the heliocentric model and Galileo improving the telescope and supporting Copernican theory. How many square meters does the Sistine Chapel ceiling cover?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Over 500 square meters"},
    {"id": "long_035", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I just finished reading about the construction of the Panama Canal, which is one of the greatest engineering achievements of the 20th century. The French initially attempted to build the canal in the 1880s under Ferdinand de Lesseps, who had successfully built the Suez Canal. However, the French effort was plagued by engineering challenges, tropical diseases (especially malaria and yellow fever), and financial problems, leading to its abandonment in 1889 after over 20,000 workers had died. The United States took over the project in 1904 under chief engineer John Frank Stevens, who convinced President Roosevelt to use a lock-based design rather than a sea-level canal. The locks raise and lower ships 26 meters between sea level and Gatun Lake. Construction employed over 75,000 workers at its peak and cost approximately $500 million (about $13 billion in today's dollars). The canal was completed in 1914, ten years after the US began work. It is approximately 82 kilometers long and saves ships about 15,000 kilometers compared to sailing around South America. An expansion completed in 2016 added a third set of wider locks to accommodate larger neo-Panamax vessels. How long is the Panama Canal?"}],
     "reference_answer": "82 kilometers"},
    {"id": "long_036", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "My doctor explained the results of my blood test in detail. My hemoglobin is 14.2 g/dL, which is within the normal range of 13.5-17.5 for adult males. My white blood cell count is 7,200 per microliter, also normal. However, my LDL cholesterol is 162 mg/dL, which is above the desirable level of under 100. My HDL cholesterol is 48 mg/dL, which should ideally be above 60. Total cholesterol is 238 mg/dL, above the recommended 200. My fasting blood glucose is 105 mg/dL, which is slightly elevated and puts me in the pre-diabetic range of 100-125. My liver enzymes ALT and AST are both within normal range at 28 and 22 U/L respectively. My thyroid function test showed TSH at 2.5 mIU/L, which is normal. My vitamin D level is 22 ng/mL, which is slightly low as the optimal range is 30-50. The doctor recommended dietary changes to address the cholesterol, exercise for the blood sugar, and a vitamin D supplement. What is my LDL cholesterol level?"}],
     "reference_answer": "162 mg/dL"},
    {"id": "long_037", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The International Space Station is a marvel of international cooperation and engineering. Construction began in 1998 with the launch of the Russian Zarya module. The station orbits Earth at an altitude of approximately 408 kilometers, traveling at about 28,000 km/h, completing one orbit every 90 minutes. This means astronauts aboard the ISS see 16 sunrises and sunsets every day. The station has been continuously occupied since November 2000, making it the longest continuous human presence in space. The habitable volume of the station is approximately 388 cubic meters, about the size of a six-bedroom house. Solar arrays spanning 2,500 square meters provide power. The station has hosted over 270 astronauts and cosmonauts from 21 countries. The total cost of the ISS is estimated at over $150 billion, making it the most expensive single structure ever built. Research aboard the station covers areas including biology, human physiology, physics, astronomy, and meteorology. The station is expected to operate until 2030, after which it will be deorbited and replaced by commercial space stations. At what altitude does the ISS orbit Earth?"}],
     "reference_answer": "408 kilometers"},
    {"id": "long_038", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I'm writing a report on the history of the internet. ARPANET, the precursor to the internet, was created by the US Department of Defense in 1969, initially connecting four universities: UCLA, Stanford Research Institute, UC Santa Barbara, and the University of Utah. The first message sent over ARPANET was 'lo' — the system crashed before the full word 'login' could be transmitted. The TCP/IP protocol suite, developed by Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn, became the standard networking protocol in 1983, which is considered the birthday of the modern internet. The Domain Name System (DNS) was introduced in 1984. Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web at CERN in 1989, creating the first web browser and web server. The first website, info.cern.ch, went live on August 6, 1991. Mosaic, the first popular graphical web browser, was released in 1993. By 1995, the internet had been commercialized, and companies like Amazon, eBay, and Yahoo were founded. Google was founded in 1998 by Larry Page and Sergey Brin. Today, over 5.3 billion people use the internet, approximately 66% of the world's population. How many universities were initially connected by ARPANET?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Four universities"},
    {"id": "long_039", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Our biology class covered the structure of DNA in detail today. DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, is a double-helix molecule composed of two strands running in opposite directions. Each strand is made of nucleotides, which consist of a sugar (deoxyribose), a phosphate group, and one of four nitrogenous bases: adenine (A), thymine (T), guanine (G), and cytosine (C). Adenine pairs with thymine via two hydrogen bonds, while guanine pairs with cytosine via three hydrogen bonds. The human genome contains approximately 3.2 billion base pairs distributed across 23 pairs of chromosomes. Only about 1.5% of the genome codes for proteins, while the rest was once called junk DNA but is now known to include regulatory elements and other functional sequences. DNA replication is carried out by the enzyme DNA polymerase, which can add about 1,000 nucleotides per second in humans. The double-helix structure was discovered by James Watson and Francis Crick in 1953, with crucial X-ray crystallography data provided by Rosalind Franklin. The complete human genome was first sequenced in 2003 as part of the Human Genome Project, which took 13 years and cost approximately $2.7 billion. How many base pairs are in the human genome?"}],
     "reference_answer": "3.2 billion base pairs"},
    {"id": "long_040", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The electric vehicle market has undergone a dramatic transformation in the past decade. Tesla, founded in 2003, pioneered the premium EV market with the Roadster (2008), Model S (2012), Model X (2015), Model 3 (2017), and Model Y (2020). In 2023, Tesla delivered approximately 1.8 million vehicles globally. Traditional automakers have responded aggressively. Volkswagen Group plans to release 25 new electric models by 2025. GM invested $35 billion in EV and autonomous vehicle development through 2025. Ford's F-150 Lightning electric pickup truck received over 200,000 reservations before launch. Chinese companies like BYD, NIO, and XPeng are also major players, with BYD surpassing Tesla in total EV sales in Q4 2023. The global EV market reached 14 million units sold in 2023, representing about 18% of all new car sales. Battery technology continues to improve, with costs falling from over $1,000 per kWh in 2010 to about $139 per kWh in 2023. Charging infrastructure is expanding rapidly, with over 2.7 million public charging points worldwide. The biggest challenge remains charging speed and range anxiety, though new models routinely achieve over 400 km of range. How many EVs were sold globally in 2023?"}],
     "reference_answer": "14 million"},
    {"id": "long_041", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I need to summarize the details of the treaty we discussed in international relations class. The Treaty of Westphalia, signed in 1648, ended the Thirty Years' War in the Holy Roman Empire and the Eighty Years' War between Spain and the Dutch Republic. The treaty is considered a pivotal moment in the development of the modern international system because it established the principle of state sovereignty — the idea that each state has exclusive sovereignty over its territory and domestic affairs, without external interference. The negotiations involved 194 states and took seven years, from 1641 to 1648. The peace was actually two separate treaties signed in the Westphalian cities of Osnabruck and Munster. Key provisions included recognition of the independence of the Netherlands and Switzerland, territorial adjustments across Europe, and provisions for religious tolerance within the Holy Roman Empire. France and Sweden emerged as major powers, while the authority of the Holy Roman Emperor was significantly diminished. The treaty established the Congress system of settling international disputes through negotiation rather than warfare, which influenced later developments like the Concert of Europe and the United Nations. How many states were involved in the negotiations?"}],
     "reference_answer": "194 states"},
    {"id": "long_042", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The James Webb Space Telescope, launched on December 25, 2021, is the most powerful space telescope ever built. It is a joint project of NASA, ESA, and the Canadian Space Agency, with a total cost of approximately $10 billion over 25 years of development. The telescope features a 6.5-meter gold-coated primary mirror made of 18 hexagonal segments, compared to Hubble's 2.4-meter mirror. It operates primarily in the infrared spectrum, allowing it to see through dust clouds and observe the most distant galaxies in the universe. The telescope orbits the Sun at the second Lagrange point (L2), approximately 1.5 million kilometers from Earth. One of its first major discoveries was the detection of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere of exoplanet WASP-39b. It has also provided the deepest and sharpest infrared images of the distant universe ever taken, showing galaxies as they appeared over 13 billion years ago. The telescope's sunshield, which is about the size of a tennis court, keeps the instruments at an operating temperature of about -233 degrees Celsius. What is the diameter of the James Webb Space Telescope's primary mirror?"}],
     "reference_answer": "6.5 meters"},
    {"id": "long_043", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The human brain is arguably the most complex structure in the known universe. It contains approximately 86 billion neurons, each connected to thousands of other neurons through synapses, creating an estimated 100 trillion synaptic connections. The brain weighs about 1.4 kilograms, roughly 2% of body weight, yet consumes about 20% of the body's total energy. The cerebral cortex, the outermost layer, is only about 2-4 millimeters thick but contains most of the brain's neurons. It is divided into four lobes: frontal (responsible for planning, decision-making, and personality), parietal (processes sensory information), temporal (involved in memory and language), and occipital (processes visual information). The brain can process information at speeds of up to 120 meters per second along myelinated neurons. Neuroplasticity, the brain's ability to reorganize itself by forming new neural connections, continues throughout life, though it is most pronounced during childhood. The hippocampus, essential for forming new memories, is one of the few brain regions where neurogenesis (new neuron growth) occurs in adults. What percentage of the body's energy does the brain consume?"}],
     "reference_answer": "20%"},
    {"id": "long_044", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I recently learned about the logistics of running a major music festival. The Glastonbury Festival in England is one of the world's largest, attracting approximately 210,000 people to Worthy Farm in Somerset. The festival site covers 900 acres and features over 100 stages and performance areas. Setting up takes about 6 weeks before the event, and dismantling takes another 6 weeks. The festival generates over 2,000 tons of waste, though recycling rates have improved to about 61% in recent years. Over 4,000 toilets are installed across the site. The festival employs approximately 30,000 workers including security, medical staff, sound engineers, and food vendors. There are over 700 food stalls offering everything from traditional British fare to international cuisine. Medical teams handle about 5,000 patient visits over the five-day event. The festival generates approximately 100 million pounds for the local economy. A single ticket costs about 340 pounds and typically sells out within hours. The festival was first held in 1970 and has been organized by Michael Eavis ever since. How many tons of waste does the festival generate?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Over 2,000 tons"},
    {"id": "long_045", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Our research team has been analyzing the economic impact of remote work adoption since the pandemic. Before 2020, approximately 5% of the US workforce worked remotely full-time. By mid-2020, that figure had jumped to about 42%. As of 2024, approximately 28% of the US workforce works in a hybrid model and 12.7% works fully remote. Companies that have embraced remote work report average cost savings of $11,000 per remote worker per year, primarily from reduced office space and overhead. However, a Stanford study found that fully remote workers were 10-20% less productive than in-office workers for collaborative tasks, though individual focused work productivity actually increased by 13%. The commercial real estate market has been significantly affected, with office vacancy rates reaching 19.6% nationally in 2024, the highest in 30 years. On the employee side, surveys show that 65% of workers would accept a pay cut of up to 5% to maintain remote work flexibility. The geographic redistribution of workers has also had impacts, with housing prices rising in previously affordable cities as remote workers relocated from expensive metro areas. What percentage of US workers worked remotely full-time before 2020?"}],
     "reference_answer": "5%"},
    {"id": "long_046", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The construction of the Burj Khalifa in Dubai is a remarkable engineering story. Standing at 828 meters tall with 163 floors, it is the tallest structure ever built. Construction began in 2004 and was completed in 2009, with the grand opening on January 4, 2010. The project employed over 12,000 workers at peak construction. The building's design, by architect Adrian Smith of Skidmore, Owings & Merrill, was inspired by the Hymenocallis flower. The foundation consists of a reinforced concrete mat 3.7 meters thick, supported by 194 piles drilled to a depth of 50 meters. Over 330,000 cubic meters of concrete and 39,000 metric tons of steel reinforcement were used. The building has 57 elevators and 8 escalators. The double-decker elevators travel at 10 meters per second. The total construction cost was approximately $1.5 billion. The observation deck on the 148th floor, called At the Top Sky, is the highest occupied floor accessible to the public at 555 meters. The building's exterior cladding system covers approximately 120,000 square meters. How tall is the Burj Khalifa?"}],
     "reference_answer": "828 meters"},
    {"id": "long_047", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "I attended a lecture on black holes that covered some incredible physics. A black hole forms when a massive star, typically at least 25 times the mass of our Sun, collapses at the end of its life. The boundary of a black hole is called the event horizon, beyond which nothing, not even light, can escape the gravitational pull. Stellar black holes range from about 5 to several tens of solar masses. However, supermassive black holes at the centers of galaxies can be millions to billions of solar masses. Sagittarius A*, the supermassive black hole at the center of our Milky Way galaxy, has a mass of approximately 4 million solar masses. The first direct image of a black hole was captured by the Event Horizon Telescope collaboration in 2019, showing the supermassive black hole at the center of galaxy M87, which has a mass of about 6.5 billion solar masses. Black holes emit Hawking radiation, a theoretical prediction by Stephen Hawking in 1974, which means they very slowly lose mass and could eventually evaporate, though this process would take far longer than the current age of the universe for any known black hole. What is the mass of Sagittarius A*?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Approximately 4 million solar masses"},
    {"id": "long_048", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "Let me explain the details of our company's new employee benefits package. All full-time employees receive health insurance with the company covering 85% of the premium. Dental and vision insurance are fully covered by the company. We offer a 401(k) retirement plan with the company matching contributions up to 6% of salary. New this year is a student loan repayment assistance program that contributes $200 per month toward employee student loans. We provide 20 days of paid time off per year for employees with 0-5 years of tenure, increasing to 25 days for 5-10 years, and 30 days for 10+ years. Parental leave has been expanded to 16 weeks paid for all parents regardless of gender. A wellness stipend of $1,500 per year can be used for gym memberships, fitness equipment, mental health services, or other wellness activities. The company covers up to $5,000 per year for professional development, including conferences, courses, and certifications. Remote work equipment allowance provides $2,000 upon hire for home office setup. Life insurance is provided at 2x annual salary at no cost to the employee. How much does the company contribute monthly toward student loan repayment?"}],
     "reference_answer": "$200 per month"},
    {"id": "long_049", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The archaeological discovery at Gobekli Tepe in southeastern Turkey has fundamentally changed our understanding of early human civilization. The site, discovered in 1963 but not excavated until 1995 by German archaeologist Klaus Schmidt, dates to approximately 9500 BCE, making it about 7,000 years older than Stonehenge and 6,500 years older than the oldest known pyramids. The site consists of massive stone pillars arranged in circles, with the largest pillars standing up to 5.5 meters tall and weighing up to 10 metric tons. The pillars are carved with elaborate reliefs depicting animals including foxes, lions, scorpions, vultures, and snakes. What makes the site revolutionary is that it was built by hunter-gatherers before the development of agriculture, pottery, or metalworking, challenging the long-held assumption that complex monumental architecture required settled agricultural communities. Only about 5% of the site has been excavated so far, suggesting there is much more to discover. Some researchers believe the site served as a religious center or gathering place for various nomadic groups. The discovery has led some archaeologists to hypothesize that the desire to build and maintain such ritual sites may have actually driven the transition to agriculture, rather than the other way around. How old is Gobekli Tepe approximately?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Dating to approximately 9500 BCE (about 11,500 years old)"},
    {"id": "long_050", "category": "long_context",
     "messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "The deep sea hydrothermal vent ecosystems discovered in 1977 near the Galapagos Rift fundamentally changed our understanding of life on Earth. These vents, found at depths of 2,000 to 4,000 meters, release superheated water at temperatures up to 400 degrees Celsius, rich in minerals and chemicals including hydrogen sulfide. Despite the extreme conditions — crushing pressure, complete darkness, and toxic chemicals — these vents support thriving ecosystems. The base of the food chain is chemosynthetic bacteria that convert hydrogen sulfide into energy, rather than relying on photosynthesis. These bacteria support a remarkable community of organisms including giant tube worms (Riftia pachyptila, which can grow up to 2.4 meters long), large white crabs, eyeless shrimp, and various mollusks. The tube worms have no mouth, gut, or anus; instead, they host symbiotic bacteria inside their bodies that provide them with nutrition. Some hydrothermal vent organisms thrive at temperatures up to 121 degrees Celsius, making them the most heat-tolerant organisms known. These discoveries expanded the potential range of environments that could support life, both on Earth and on other planets and moons, particularly Europa and Enceladus, which are thought to have subsurface oceans and hydrothermal activity. How long can giant tube worms grow?"}],
     "reference_answer": "Up to 2.4 meters"},
]

